      <bioghist id="aspace_02fc75bb0408efc745275f31a3aa8cde">
         <head>DANIEL MULFORD (1781-1811)</head>
         <p>Daniel Mulford, son of Jonathan Mulford, Jr. and Deborah Ludlow, was born in New Providence, New Jersey, in 1781. He received his early education at Morristown Academy under Samuel Whelpley, worked briefly as a shopkeeper in New York City, and entered Yale College in 1804. In 1806 Mulford graduated with a Bachelor of Arts degree and returned to New Jersey to teach at Morristown. He began studying law but declining health caused him to relocate to a warmer climate. In Savannah he resumed his legal education and was admitted to the Georgia Bar in 1809 despite continued ill-health. Daniel Mulford died of tuberculosis in New Providence, New Jersey, in 1811.</p>  
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_123acf8897ceb30fc4c1c125b7957c8e">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The Stephen Sylvester Day Collection of Daniel Mulford consists of letters, diaries, manuscripts, and personal papers which relate to the life of Daniel Mulford. The collection spans the dates 1801-1812 and is arranged in two series.</p>
         <p>
            <ref actuate="onrequest" show="replace" target="ref12">Series I, <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
                  <part>Correspondence</part>
               </title> 
            </ref>, is arranged in three subseries: Letters from Daniel Mulford, Letters to Daniel Mulford, and Third Party Correspondence. Each subseries is arranged alphabetically by correspondent. Letters from Daniel Mulford discuss such topics as Mulford's thoughts about Yale, religion, philosophy and his ongoing battle with tuberculosis. Letters to Daniel Mulford chiefly concern news from friends and business associates, including Philemon Dickerson and Thomas Edward Lloyd. Third Party Correspondence consists of a letter regarding Mulford's death (folder 16) as well as two letters from Isreal Russell to Daniel's brother Levi which describe Fourth of July celebrations in New York in 1807 and 1808 (folder 17).</p>
         <p>
            <ref actuate="onrequest" show="replace" target="ref33">Series II, <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
                  <part>Personal Papers</part>
               </title> 
            </ref>, is arranged in two subseries: Diaries of Daniel Mulford and Other Papers. Diaries of Daniel Mulford is arranged chronologically. The earliest diary documents his education at Morristown under Samuel Whelpley, his employment in New York City, and his years at Yale (folder 25). The two other diaries document Mulford's travels to New Haven and Georgia in 1808.</p>
         <p>Other Papers is also chronologically arranged, and includes the poem "Contentment", possibly by Mulford; a list of speakers for Yale College's 1806 commencement; several documents related to Mulford's legal career; and an undated scrapbook of Mulford's personal papers compiled by Stephen Sylvester Day.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
